  "prompt": "How can you determine the derivative of [math]\\sin x^2[/math]?",
  "response": "To determine the derivative of \\(\\sin(x^2)\\), you can use the chain rule. The chain rule states that if you have a composite function \\(f(g(x))\\), then the derivative is \\(f'(g(x)) \\cdot g'(x)\\).\n\nLet's apply this to \\(\\sin(x^2)\\):\n\n1. Let \\(u = x^2\\). Then the function becomes \\(\\sin(u)\\).\n2. The derivative of \\(\\sin(u)\\) with respect to \\(u\\) is \\(\\cos(u)\\).\n3. The derivative of \\(u = x^2\\) with respect to \\(x\\) is \\(2x\\).\n\nNow, using the chain rule, the derivative of \\(\\sin(x^2)\\) with respect to \\(x\\) is:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{d}{dx} \\sin(x^2) = \\cos(u) \\cdot \\frac{du}{dx}\n\\]\n\nSubstitute \\(u = x^2\\):\n\n\\[\n\\frac{d}{dx} \\sin(x^2) = \\cos(x^2) \\cdot 2x\n\\]\n\nTherefore, the derivative of \\(\\sin(x^2)\\) is:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{d}{dx} (\\sin(x^2)) = 2x \\cos(x^2)\n\\]",
